ny French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":8,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert Septvans, Knight was born on 5 January 1215, in Addington, Kent, England, his father, Robert de Stepvans, was 16 and his mother, Matilda, was 23. He had at least 1 daughter with Matilda. He died on 3 January 1250, in Cooling, Kent, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 34, and was buried in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"5 January 1215–3 January 1250":"5. jaanuar 1215–3. jaanuar 1250","1215–1250":"1215–1250","–1249":"–1249","1241–1298":"1241–1298","1238–1322":"1238–1322","1250–1304":"1250–1304","1200–1249":"1200–1249","1193–1253":"1193–1253","Aft 1249":"pärast 1249","1253":"1253","5 January 1215":"5. jaanuar 1215","1241":"1241","1250":"1250","3 January 1250":"3. jaanuar 1250","1193":"1193","1249":"1249","1304":"1304","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1322":"1322","1200":"1200","1298":"1298","Cooling, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Cooling, Ken